        "content": "Valen’s eyes flickered toward Merlin for a fraction of a second—a sharp, instinctive check to ensure the mage hadn't collapsed. Seeing the Magister rise, even with that telltale sway of exhaustion, allowed a microscopic amount of tension to bleed from his shoulders, though his grip on the gladius remained absolute. The device, now a lifeless husk on the ground, was a secondary concern; the primary threat was still standing at the mouth of the alley, draped in shadows that seemed to defy the laws of light.\n\n*Magister Merlin.* \n\nThe name carried weight, even in the gutter of a dark alley. Valen felt a surge of grim respect for the person behind him. To face such a draining, corruptive force and still find the breath to assert one's identity—it was the kind of iron will that defined the legends of the Arcane Council. \n\nAs Merlin spoke, Valen stepped slightly to the flank, a subtle tactical movement designed to widen his field of vision and ensure he wasn't caught in a direct line of fire should the stranger decide to strike. He moved with the practiced grace of a man used to dancing on the edge of a blade, his boots making almost no sound on the wet cobblestones.\n\nThe figure didn't flinch at the declaration of Merlin's name. If anything, the stillness grew more profound, more oppressive. The stranger’s gaze—or whatever sense they were using to perceive the world—seemed to drift from Merlin to the purified device, and then finally settled on Valen, as if acknowledging the steel held in his hand.\n\n\"Magister Merlin,\" the figure repeated. The name sounded strange in that hollow, mechanical voice, stripped of all reverence or fear. It was merely a data point, a fact to be filed away. \"Authority is a concept for those who believe in the permanence of laws. You speak of yourself as if your will is a sovereign decree.\"\n\nThe gloved hand that had gestured toward Merlin slowly lowered, but the air in the alleyway didn't settle; it grew colder, the frost beginning to bloom in thin, crystalline patterns along the edges of the nearby stone walls.\n\nValen felt the hair on his arms stand up. This wasn't just a rogue or a common assassin. There was a weight to this presence, a sense of ancient, inevitable purpose that made his skin crawl. He shifted his weight, centering his gravity, his eyes narrowed and searching for the slightest tell—a shift in the cloak, the glint of a weapon, the gathering of mana.\n\n\"The Magister has given you his name,\" Valen interjected, his voice cutting through the oppressive chill like a whetstone on steel. His tone was no longer the charming tavern patron, but the Captain of the Solitaries—sharp, authoritative, and laced with a quiet threat. \"And I have given you my attention. Now, let's skip the philosophy lesson. You've been lurking in the dark long enough. Who are you, and why are you hunting in our streets?\""
