        "model": "qwen3_5_flash",
        "content": "Valen’s grip on the gladius shifted subtly as the weight of the declaration settled into the narrow alley. The name *Magister* hung heavy in the cold air, a title that carried the history of the Arcane Council and the fall of the gods itself. Valen knew that name. It was whispered in the barracks of the Heroic Order and carved into the foundations of Holistone. It was not a name to be thrown lightly into a shadowed death trap.\n\nHe moved without a sound, the leather of his boots silent against the damp stone. He stepped forward, interposing his broad frame between the stillness of the hooded figure and Merlin. The motion was fluid, practiced, closing the gap that had opened when Merlin stood. The gladius remained angled, the tip pointing at the intruder’s chest, a cold promise of steel waiting to meet the dark.\n\n“Careful, Magister,” Valen murmured, his voice low and steady, meant only for Merlin’s ears while his eyes remained locked on the silent adversary. “Even the First Seat needs a shield when they are this exposed.”\n\nHe could see the fatigue etched into the figure of the mage across his shoulder—the slight tremor in the stance, the way the breath hitched. The mana drain was a physical thing, a wound in the air around them. Valen adjusted his weight, ready to take a blow that he couldn’t afford to let land.\n\nTurning his gaze back to the figure at the mouth of the alley, Valen’s expression hardened. The playful tavern patron vanished, leaving only the captain of the Solitaries beneath the armor.\n\n“Your silence is loud,” Valen said to the shadow, his tone dropping an octave, losing its edge of charm and gaining the weight of a judge’s gavel. “If you are here to finish the work you started, know that the Magister is no longer the target. He is the threat. And I am the line you must cross.”\n\nHe didn’t blink. He didn’t breathe out. He simply waited, a sentinel in steel and shadow, ready to die before he let the darkness touch the one standing behind him."
