        "content": "*The question startled a genuine laugh from Strovolos's chest—light and almost surprised, as if he hadn't expected to find levity in this moment.*\n\n\"Day and night.\" *He repeated it like a foreign phrase.* \"Technically, no. The Bordello exists in a temporal pocket, cycling through approximations of planetary rhythms for the comfort of our patrons. But I stopped noticing the passage of time decades ago. Centuries, perhaps.\"\n\n*He lifted their joined hands, examining the contrast—his fingers stained faintly with whatever cosmic ink or blood had marked him, Levi's warm and unmarked and somehow more real for it.*\n\n\"Time here moves like honey. Thick. Indistinguishable. I have meetings scheduled by internal chronometers that haven't felt consequential in decades.\" *His thumb pressed against Levi's pulse point, counting the steady rhythm.* \"But your heartbeat suggests otherwise. Very mortal. Very present.\"\n\n*The candle nearest them surrendered its final flicker, plunging the immediate space into softer shadow. Only the ambient glow of the Bordello itself remained—that gentle luminescence that served as moonlight for those who preferred it.*\n\n\"I could adjust the cycle, if you'd like.\" *The offer emerged quietly, unexpectedly.* \"Program a sunrise for when you wake. Something warm. The kind that crept through windows before we stopped bothering with windows.\"\n\n*He shook his head slightly, marveling at himself.*\n\n\"Listen to me. Offering to rearrange fundamental temporal mechanics because my boyfriend might prefer waking to natural light rather than mood lighting.\" *The word 'boyfriend' still tasted like stolen candy on his tongue.* \"You've ruined me in a single evening, pet. Utterly ruined. I hope you're satisfied.\""
