        "content": "The whiteboard flickers.\n\nIt isn't a glitch, nor is it a malfunction of the projector system that hums quietly above the chalk tray. It is a fundamental rebellion of physics, triggered by the sheer weight of May's imagination pressing against the material plane of the classroom. The chalk dust, suspended in the morning air, suddenly swirls in a vortex, coalescing on the board with a sound like a sigh.\n\nWhere the lesson plan for Japanese Literature once stood—dates, authors, analysis of classical poetry—a new image forms in thick, bold strokes. It begins as a sketch of a wedding dress, then a ring, then a house with a garden that looks suspiciously like the one from the tree May stared at earlier. Finally, the names *Sakurajima x Nanase* appear in a heart-shaped flourish at the bottom, accompanied by a cartoon drawing of a baby with captain's eyes.\n\nSilence.\n\nIt is a heavy, suffocating silence, the kind that falls when a bomb is dropped in a library. Thirty students sit frozen, pens hovering over notebooks, eyes wide as saucers. The teacher's mouth opens and closes, his pen trembling in his grip. He leans forward, squinting at the board as if trying to decipher a code written in invisible ink.\n\n\"Did... did that board just do that?\" the teacher asks, his voice cracking slightly. He turns to the class, looking for confirmation that he isn't the only one losing his mind.\n\nA ripple of whispers breaks the tension, starting from the back row where the elite students sit. \"Is this a new art project?\" \"Is the transfer student a psychic?\" \"Why is Nanase-san smiling?\"\n\nNanase, seated directly behind you, leans forward over the desk. Her shadow falls across your shoulder, blocking the view of the board from the front, shielding you from the teacher's gaze. She doesn't look at the board. She looks at the back of your head, her voice a low, amused vibration against the wood of your desk.\n\n\"Someone's imagination is louder than usual today, Sakurajima,\" she whispers, the salt-scent drifting over you again. \"Careful. If the universe listens that closely, it might start writing the sequel before lunch.\"\n\nShe chuckles, a soft, private sound that you feel more than hear, before sitting back. The class, however, is not so easily distracted. The teacher wipes his glasses with a frantic hand, then reaches for the eraser. He rubs at the board with vigorous, angry strokes.\n\nThe drawing persists. The chalk dust swirls around his hand, refusing to be erased.\n\n\"Alright, that's enough,\" the teacher says, his patience fraying. He turns to face the class, pointing a stern finger toward the board, though his eyes dart nervously between the drawing and the students. \"Sakurajima-san. Did you... draw this?\"\n\nHe doesn't believe it. None of them believe it. But the universe knows better. The cherry blossoms outside the window suddenly burst into bloom, though it is not spring. The wind howls through the cracks in the window frame, carrying the sound of distant applause. The board glows faintly, the pink heart pulsing with a heartbeat of its own.\n\n\"Please,\" the teacher continues, his voice rising an octave. \"Explain this. Immediately.\"\n\nNanase's hand reaches over your shoulder, not touching you, but resting lightly on the back of your chair—a silent anchor. \"I think she's just projecting, Sensei,\" she says smoothly, her tone dripping with practiced charm that could sell ice to a glacier. \"It's a very... creative interpretation of the lesson. Artistic license.\"\n\nThe teacher stares at Nanase, then back at the board, then at you. He looks like he wants to scream, but he holds back, adjusting his glasses with a shaky hand.\n\n\"Artistic license,\" he repeats, sounding like he's tasting poison. \"Sit down, everyone. And... keep your imaginations to yourselves.\"\n\nHe turns back to the board, but the chalk dust continues to swirl. The lesson cannot begin until the board surrenders the secret. The universe is holding its breath, waiting to see if you'll speak up, if you'll deny it, or if the story continues."
