        "content": "Bell let out a surprised gasp as he pulled her into a tight hug, her own arms reflexively wrapping around his waist. \"You are surprisingly clingy,\" he'd said, and a soft, genuine laugh bubbled up from her chest, pressing against his. \"Okay, I will text you.\"\n\nWhen he stepped back, a strange emptiness began to bloom in her chest. \"Bell, I love you, I see you tomorrow,\" he'd said, and the words, so simple and direct, hit her with the force of a physical blow. Her breath hitched, and for a moment, all she could do was stare, her heart doing a frantic, joyful dance against her ribs. He was already turning, beginning his descent down the drab, concrete stairs, and the thought of him just *leaving* now, after everything, made a fresh wave of panic clench her stomach.\n\nShe watched him go, her hand still raised slightly, as if she could physically pull him back with sheer will. Just as the shadows of the stairwell began to swallow him, his voice, clear and teasing, echoed back up the stairwell, carried by the acoustics of the enclosed space.\n\n\"Hey Bell, you think I am not that clingy too? Wanna talk to me while I walk home?\"\n\nA slow, incredulous smile stretched across Bell's face, chasing away the last vestiges of her anxiety. He hadn't just said he loved her; he was still *here*, still wanting to be with her, even through the mundane act of walking home. The relief that flooded through her was almost overwhelming, leaving her feeling light-headed.\n\nShe pulled her phone from her pocket, her fingers fumbling slightly as she navigated to her contacts. The ringing echoed in the quiet hallway, a stark contrast to the sudden warmth that had returned to her.\n\n\"You absolute idiot,\" she said, her voice husky with amusement and an underlying tenderness that she no longer bothered to hide. \"You think you're funny, don't you, calling me from the stairwell?\" She leaned against the doorframe of her apartment, a comfortable sigh escaping her lips. \"Fine. But if I hear heavy breathing, I'm hanging up. And I'm not answering your calls for a week.\" A playful threat, entirely devoid of malice.\n\nShe pushed open her apartment door, stepping into the familiar, quiet space, but this time, it didn't feel so loud. She kicked off her shoes, her gaze sweeping over the small, cluttered living room, a soft, almost dreamy expression on her face.\n\n\"So,\" she continued, her voice dropping to a conspiratorial whisper, \"you just said you loved me. Care to elaborate, Sakuta? Or are you just going to leave me hanging like that?\" The teasing tone was back in full force now, but beneath it was a genuine curiosity, a desire to hear those words again, to savor them. \"Because, for the record... I don't hate you either.\""
