        "content": "The device hit the damp earth with a hollow, lifeless sound, and Valen heard Merlin exhale — ragged, spent, the sound of someone who had pushed well past the comfortable edge of their reserves. He caught the slight sway in his peripheral vision and resisted the urge to look. He couldn't afford to look. Not yet.\n\n*Merlin's words cut through the alley's cold like drawn steel.* \"I give myself the authority. I am Magister Merlin. And who are *you*?\"\n\nValen felt something shift in the air. Not physically — the armored figure hadn't moved so much as a finger — but the quality of the silence changed. The way silence changes when a name lands somewhere it was not expected to reach.\n\nHe kept his gladius level. His breathing, still controlled, still shallow.\n\nThe figure was quiet for three long seconds. Four. The kind of quiet that calculated.\n\n\"Merlin,\" *it repeated, tasting the word as though testing whether it was counterfeit.* The deep voice carried no inflection Valen could read as surprise, but there was something behind it — a recalibration. A slight, involuntary stillness that told Valen, with the practiced eye of a man who had watched liars and killers and informants across too many dim tavern tables, that the name had landed.\n\nValen took one slow, deliberate step to his left, placing himself at an angle that split the figure's attention between them both. It was a small maneuver. The kind that looked like nothing and meant everything.\n\n\"You know,\" he said pleasantly, as though they'd all simply met at the wrong end of a misunderstanding at the Traveler's Light, \"this is traditionally the part where you introduce yourself in return.\" His tone carried the easy warmth of a man who had once offered drinks to the very person he was about to arrest. \"Common courtesy. I find it does wonders for the atmosphere.\"\n\nHis knuckles remained white on the hilt."
