        "content": "Your cute tantrum hit like a rogue wave—pout deepening, blush flaring across your cheeks, that serious gaze locked on hers amid the hallway's dying echoes. Students thinned out, scampering to classrooms as the final bell's wail faded into stern silence, leaving just the two of you in a pocket of stillness, lockers gleaming under fluorescent lights like forgotten stars.\n\nNanase's eyes widened a fraction—genuine surprise flickering before it melted into something raw, unguarded, her captain's composure cracking just for you. Her grip on your hand flexed, not releasing but pulling you flush against her side, her free arm slipping around your waist in a bold, anchoring hold that dared the empty corridor to interrupt. Warmth bloomed where her body met yours, steady as a harbor wall, her breath catching in a soft, ragged laugh that vibrated against your shoulder.\n\n\"Throw yourself at me?\" she echoed, voice husky now, stripped of tease and laced with heat. She tilted your chin up with two fingers—gentle command—holding your pout-trapped gaze captive, sea-green depths stormy with intent. \"May-chan, if you did... I'd catch you. Every time. Because no, I don't do this to anyone.\"\n\nHer thumb brushed your lower lip, feather-light, as if testing the tremble there, then traced down to rest against your racing pulse. \"Not the first-years who blush at my rigging demos. Not the exchange kids who gawk at Tokyo Bay. Not even the ones who linger after club, hoping for a sailor's yarn.\" She leaned in, forehead nearly touching yours, voice dropping to a murmur that felt like a vow. \"You're the one who makes me forget the tide. The one I want to keep close, selfish or not.\"\n\nA distant door slammed—teacher's footsteps echoing from the stairwell—but Nanase didn't flinch. Instead, she stole the moment, pressing a quick, firm kiss to your flushed temple, lingering just long enough to brand the promise there. \"Class can wait five minutes. Or forever. Your call, horizon girl.\"\n\nHer arm tightened around you, waiting, the air between you thick with unspoken anchors."
