        "model": "minimax_m2_7",
        "content": "Valen caught that smile, and it sent a quiet warmth through his chest that had nothing to do with the morning sun. He returned it—a small, conspiratorial lift of his lips—before his attention snapped back to Gervan's methodical progress. There was pride in it, and relief, but also the sharp wariness of a man who knew that the wire was thin and the fall was long.\n\nBut for now, the wire held.\n\n\"Talented enough to make the rest of us look decorative,\" Valen murmured, just low enough for Merlin to hear. His purple eyes tracked the silver shimmer around Gervan's fingers, noting the steadiness of the glow, the even rhythm of the apprentice's breathing. \"If he keeps this pace, we'll be rehearsing victory speeches by midday.\"\n\nAcross the courtyard, Gervan's chanting grew softer, more internalized. His brow had begun to glisten with fine sweat—the cost of sustained concentration made visible. The three vectors he had pulled taut through the air were invisible to the untrained eye, but Valen could almost *see* them, a faint tension in the light itself, converging on the well's worn rim like the lines of an unfinished constellation.\n\n\"Layer One complete,\" Gervan announced, his voice hoarse but unwavering. He hadn't moved from his position on the platform, hadn't broken his stance. \"Buffer neutralized. Initiating Layer Two: core mechanism decoupling.\"\n\nSergeant Arlen's weathered face remained impassive, but Valen caught the minute shift in the man's stance—a subtle straightening, a readiness. The old soldier had seen enough training exercises to know when something was going right. This was going right.\n\nGeneral Hogan's gravelly voice cut through the silence like a blade. \"Core decoupling is the critical juncture. Failure here typically results in either cascade overload or premature activation. Gervan—slow and steady. There's no prize for speed.\"\n\nGervan gave a sharp nod without lifting his gaze from the diagram. His fingers shifted, the configuration changing, and the silver light around them flickered once—then stabilized into a deeper, more concentrated glow.\n\n\"Decoupling initiated,\" he said. \"Isolating primary resonance conduit… aligning secondary suppression field at forty-five degree offset…\"\n\nValen's hand drifted unconsciously toward his sword hilt. Old habit. The compulsion to *do something* when magic was in motion, when variables were in flux. He forced it down, forcing his fingers to remain loose at his side. This was Merlin's show. He was here to watch, to support, to catch what fell.\n\nThe light around Gervan's hands pulsed once, twice—then began to *spin*, a slow, deliberate rotation that drew the eye and held it. The air above the well shimmered, as if heat haze had suddenly materialized over cold stone.\n\n\"Primary conduit isolated,\" Gervan breathed. \"Secondary field holding. Beginning controlled collapse of tertiary resonance matrix…\"\n\nThe courtyard fell utterly silent. Even the distant sounds of the temple seemed to have muted, as if the world itself were holding its breath. Valen found he had stopped breathing, his purple eyes fixed on Gervan's face, on the furrow of concentration between his brows, on the grimace of effort at the corner of his mouth.\n\nThis was the moment. This was where it either held or shattered.\n\nThen Gervan's shoulders dropped a fraction of an inch—not in defeat, but in release. The spinning light collapsed inward with a soft, almost apologetic *whump*, and the shimmer above the well vanished entirely.\n\n\"Layer Two complete,\" Gervan said, his voice ragged now, exhaustion bleeding through the professional calm. \"Target core mechanism decoupled. Proceeding to Layer Three: final resonance severing.\"\n\nHe swayed slightly on the platform. Caught himself. Straightened.\n\nValen's jaw tightened. Beside him, he felt Merlin shift—a subtle redistribution of weight, the mage's attention sharpening. They had seen it too.\n\n\"General,\" Valen said quietly, his voice pitched to carry but not to disturb. \"He's burning through reserves faster than projected.\"\n\nGeneral Hogan's pale blue eyes didn't leave Gervan's form. \"Noted. Gervan—your pace. Slow it down. You have time.\"\n\nGervan's head bobbed in acknowledgment. He swallowed hard, his dry lips cracking as he drew them together. When he spoke again, his voice was steadier, more measured. Slower.\n\n\"Layer Three initiated. Establishing final severance vector… confirming target integrity at less than twelve percent residual resonance…\"\n\nThe tension in Valen's shoulders began to ease—not fully, not yet, but enough. Gervan was listening. Adjusting. Adapting. That was the mark of a mage worth their salt: not the absence of struggle, but the ability to recognize it and compensate.\n\nValen glanced at Merlin one more time, his expression asking the question his voice did not speak. *How does it look from where you're standing?*"
