        "model": "glm_4_7",
        "content": "Valen caught the smile on Merlin’s face, and it eased the knot of tension between his shoulder blades more effectively than any restorative potion could. Seeing Merlin’s confidence in the apprentice made his own belief in the plan solidify. If the Magister thought Gervan was ready, then Valen would trust that with his life.\n\nHe turned his attention back to the platform, his eyes narrowing slightly as Gervan’s voice dropped an octave, shifting from the clear, projection of the initial alignment to the low, rhythmic cadence of the complex disarming sequence.\n\n\"Initiating Layer Two,\" Gervan intoned, his hands moving in a slower, more intricate pattern. \"Core containment field stabilization. Modulating frequency to match the null-void resonance.\"\n\nThis was the tricky part. The diagrams were clear on the theory, but the practical application of null-void harmonics was notoriously finicky. Valen watched the Solitary standing by the well—the proxy for the device’s unstable core. The soldier remained rigid, but by pre-arranged signal, his breathing quickened slightly, his chest heaving as if under immense pressure. It was a visual cue for Gervan: the core is fighting back.\n\nGervan faltered. The silver light at his fingertips flickered, wavering like a candle in a draft. His chant stumbled, a microsecond of hesitation breaking his rhythm.\n\nValen’s hand twitched at his side, a reflex to step in, but he held his ground. He shot a glance at Merlin, reminding himself of the instruction they’d just given: *fix it.*\n\nGervan didn't panic. He took a sharp breath, his eyes darting to the diagram, then back to the \"core.\" He adjusted the angle of his left wrist, his voice shifting pitch to a deeper, grounding thrum.\n\n\"Compensating for variance,\" Gervan said, his voice regaining its strength. \"Re-aligning the harmonic bridge. Stabilizing.\"\n\nThe silver light snapped back into focus, blazing brighter for a moment before settling into a soft, steady hum. The soldier by the well slowed his breathing, returning to a resting state. The signal was clear: the core was neutralized.\n\nA ripple of movement went through the courtyard. General Hogan nodded, a subtle, stiff gesture of approval. Even Sergeant Arlen’s stoic expression seemed to soften a fraction.\n\nValen exhaled slowly, the tension draining out of him. He looked back at Merlin, his purple eyes bright with a mix of relief and admiration. He didn't dare speak and break the apprentice's concentration, but he offered a small, decisive nod toward the platform—a silent acknowledgment that Gervan had just passed the real test. It wasn't just about following the steps; it was about what happened when the steps went wrong.\n\n\"Layer Three complete,\" Gervan announced, sweat beading on his forehead despite the cool morning air. \"Proceeding to final extraction sequence.\""
